Gtex Disgenet analysis

This document shows how the correlation between tissue and disease is revealed by analyzing a gtex dataset Median gene-level TPM by tissue() and Curated gene-disease associations from Disgenet().

Preparation

Load packages

library(tidyverse)
library(Biostrings)
library(pathview)

ggplot2: for plotting tidyverse: -ggplot2:data visualization -dplyr:data manipulation -tidyr:data tidying -stringr:for strings Biostrings:for mapping gene names

First, the two datasets are download from Gtex and Disgenet websites, and then imported to the environment.(gene_t is converted to csv)

gene_t<-read_csv("Gene_T.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Name = col_character(),
##   Description = col_character()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
gene_d<-read_tsv("Gene_C.tsv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   geneId = col_double(),
##   geneSymbol = col_character(),
##   DSI = col_double(),
##   DPI = col_double(),
##   diseaseId = col_character(),
##   diseaseName = col_character(),
##   diseaseType = col_character(),
##   diseaseClass = col_character(),
##   diseaseSemanticType = col_character(),
##   score = col_double(),
##   EI = col_double(),
##   YearInitial = col_double(),
##   YearFinal = col_double(),
##   NofPmids = col_double(),
##   NofSnps = col_double(),
##   source = col_character()
## )

tidying

It is observed that in gene_d and gene_t, the same gene name is used sothat theres no need for conversion. However, its still necessary to see whether each gene in the disease dataset can match to a gene in the tissue dataset.

gene_t<-gene_t%>%
  mutate(Name=gsub("\\..*","",Name))
nope<-distinct(gene_d,geneSymbol,geneId)%>%
  mutate(is=geneSymbol %in% gene_t$Description)%>%
  filter(!is)
nope
## # A tibble: 247 x 3
##    geneSymbol geneId is   
##    <chr>       <dbl> <lgl>
##  1 ALPG          251 FALSE
##  2 ATP5F1A       498 FALSE
##  3 ATP5F1B       506 FALSE
##  4 ATP5F1D       513 FALSE

##  7 CECR         1055 FALSE
##  8 DCR          1637 FALSE
##  9 GSDME        1687 FALSE
## 10 DGCR         1714 FALSE
## #  with 237 more rows

Among the 9411 distinct genes in the disease dataset, there are 247 genes that arent in the tissue data. Based on some other observations, theres no other reasons for this, the GTEX data (gene_t) simply doesnt include these genes.

So we can remove them, although this may affect the final result.

gene_dd<-gene_d%>%
  anti_join(nope,by="geneSymbol")

Method 1

First, arrange by disease ID

gene_ddd<-gene_dd%>%
  arrange(diseaseId)
disease_name<-(gene_ddd%>%distinct(diseaseId))$diseaseId

create the target dataframe

gene_disease_tissue<-colnames(gene_t)[3:56]
all_relation<-data.frame(matrix(ncol = 55, nrow = 10280))
colnames(all_relation)<-c(list("Disease"),gene_disease_tissue)
all_relation$Disease=disease_name
#This is the target datafram
for(i in 2:55){
  all_relation[i]=rep(0,10280)
}

Next step is (quite complicated) For each disease, there are several genes realted to it,(disgenet data) we sum up the expression level of each of these genes in each tissue to gain the disease-tissue relationship.
